revised the motor mount to make the nut wells tighter, for nuts with <5mm outer hex edge to edge. NOTE: if you are unsure about the nut you are using, just get the first design. Cheers!
I designed this using Autodesk fusion 360.

About the design

we had bought a whiteboard but no pen holder was provided with it. So i decided to make a magnetic one. Bonus point if it can be customisable.

Features

Customise number of pens, pens diameter, magnets height and magnets diameter.

How to assemble

Get some magnets and some pens. Put the magnets in the holes of the back, put the pens in the hole on the top and put the holder against a metallic surface. Done !

Limits

Because of some laziness, hole to receive pens are limited to 13mm in diameters and 4 holes maximum are made for magnets. So if you need a 20 pen holder with 8 magnets, maybe you will need to fiddle with the code.

This is a sliding test lead or cable rack made from a tie rack, and some 3D printed hangers.  I've always liked the functionality of test lead racks, but don't like how they look.  This allows me to hide the test leads under a workbench, and keep them out of sight.

The sliding tie rack can be found here: http://www.leevalley.com/en/Garden/page.aspx?p=49349&cat=2,42194,67373. Print as many hangers as you need to fill the rack. I've included two sizes for slots of 4mm, and 6mm, which worked for my mix of test leads. I used 26 fingers on a 20" tie rack, but since I don't have access to the full length, I filled it up with some of the clips that came with the tie rack. I printed these out of PLA, with 2 shells, and a 50% honeycomb infill. Carefully pry one of the plastic ends off of the rack, and remove the tie hangers. Slide the printed hangers in, and replace the end cap that you removed. The hangers fit pretty tight in the rack, and on a few of them it took a small amount of filing to get them to slide in easily. You may need to use a small amount of glue to get the end cap to stay in place again. If you have Geomagic Design, Cubify, or Alibre, you can modify the included CAD file to create whatever slot size, or hanger length you would like.

description.text:
I use alot of shopping bags as garbage bins, so I made this so I can hang them on doors and the like. The top edge is tapered and designed around fitting into the 3m command adhesive hooks. Look at the photo's for how to put the shopping bag in, but its pretty straight forward.

Depending on the size of your shopping bag, you might want to scale it in the z direction

In order to make it:

  1. Print both left and right stl's
  2. On one side, insert some 1.75mm filament in the holes in the arms of the print
  3. glue the filament in place
  4. Join the left and right using the filament as the joiner between the two sides
  5. glue a bit more.
  6. hang on a wall using some form of hook from the top of the print

In one of the images you can see mine hanging by only one hook, but in reality its better to use two, both for strength and to keep it straight. The pictures show a previous version that doesn't have a strut to help with the weight of the garbage, so the version on thingiverse is actually quite a bit beefed up for handling extra weight.

A desktop machine that will measure out a length of wire and strip a length from either end.
(a video of it in operation: http://www.youtube.com/watch?v=F2O7kGE34EA ) Why?
To create lengths of wire that fit perfectly into an electronics breadboard. (we produce kits and you can only hand cut and strip so many wires before you go crazy) This is also the first item in a concept oomlout.com is working on dubbed "open manufacturing". (more to follow) How?
It breaks down into three parts
  • Wire Feeder - This feeds the wire in measured lengths forwards and backwards (uses a stepper motor)
  • Wire Stripper - This runs an exacto knife blade around the insulation of the wire twice. (uses a small servo motor and normal sized servo motor)
  • Wire Snipper - Snips the wire at the end. (uses a pair of wire cutters and a cheap handheld drill motor)

Made using a combination of 1/4" and 1/8" Acrylic.
I fear the details are a tad complex this is added more as a curio but if you would like to build one yourself, send me a message and I can help out with the details (or if enough people are interested I'll hash it out a tad further)
(Also included is the Arduino Software to run it)

description.text:
I needed to improve my filament support system and thought a good way for doing so was to use some spool adapters I've seen here in Thingiverse. Unhappily, other designs I found didn't work very well for me, mostly for the wide range of spool sizes I use (from small 250g spools to 1kg spools from different sellers here in Brazil).

So this thing consists in 2 identical conical adapters that are used to centralize the spool to a 5/8" threaded rod and a common bearing (608 series) in each side, holding it all together with compatible nuts in both sides, providing effortless filament feeding to the extruder.

It should fit filament spools with central holes between 30mm and 75mm.

I included the original files (SolidWorks) in case anyone wants to tweak it a little bit.

For the printing, I used a 0.6mm nozzle with 0.3mm resolution, 2 vertical shells and 20-30% infill.

description.text:
This year Neutral Digital was hired to create a VR experience based on Air Canada's Boeing 787 Dreamliner. During our testing, we encountered a continual issue where users would accidentally click the ‘Oculus Home’ button on the controllers, disrupting the experience.

After finding out the button couldn't be disabled via software we decided a physical cap would be the best solution as it would disable the button and improve the aesthetics of the controller for the exhibition spaces it would be installed in.

Please note: There are separate caps for the left and right controllers, please check the files before you print.

Infill:

Enough for sanding

Notes:

We printed these caps on multiple different printers:

Objet Connecx3 260 - Printed with Objets VeroWhitePlus and standard support materials. Gave a great finish, required minimal sanding and priming to bring it to a professional finish.

Ultimaker 2 - Printed with a standard black ABS. Comes out of the printer much rougher and will require a substantial amount of sanding and primer filler to get a smooth finish. If possible print base down and use support materials in the button holes to allow the face to print smoothly. Then remove the supports using a rotary tool.

Print with enough infill to allow for sanding.
